elements.2211.03020_ba254e03724341366f7f9753f0fde: Learning from demonstration (LfD) is a proven technique to teach robots new skills
elements.2211.03020_a7e8b602d6e0538396f278d7f544e: Data quality and quantity play a critical role in LfD trained model performance
elements.2211.03020_ea4306f495bb770e9ca50cdf75514: In this paper we analyze the effect of enhancing an existing teleoperation data collection system with real-time haptic feedback; we observe improvements in the collected data throughput and its quality for model training
elements.2211.03020_fbf04aa52c435fc8695067adf6c8c: Our experiment testbed was a mobile manipulator robot that opened doors with latch handles
elements.2211.03020_7c06b1dea2d6992541d15d3b0c07b: Evaluation of teleoperated data collection on eight real world conference room doors found that adding the haptic feedback improved the data throughput by 6
elements.2211.03020_7116330e6c0d0ddcd6a4642a3dc41: We additionally used the collected data to train six image-based deep imitation learning models, three with haptic feedback and three without it
elements.2211.03020_3aad4ccfcce5ae3356667e075611f: These models were used to implement autonomous door-opening with the same type of robot used during data collection
elements.2211.03020_02097425e33684b154c8be86cb4ad: Our results show that a policy from a behavior cloning model trained with haptic data performed on average 11
elements.2211.03020_a962022c3c935e065df49796d0c5e: better than its counterpart with no haptic feedback data, indicating that haptic feedback resulted in collection of a higher quality dataset.
elements.2211.03020_5c3a049ff6dc9e37b19f20e645dee: Haptics and Haptic Interfaces, Imitation Learning
elements.2211.03020_b0bcf6f87a94c9805bb18621f5298: Learning from demonstration is a promising approach to teach robots new skills based on a set of expert demonstrations
elements.2211.03020_5b40e813f04dfb758b30b6dc762b2: In this paradigm, the learned policy benefits from the demonstrators' prior knowledge about a task (in contrast to self exploration) in order to learn the task with a reasonable number of demonstrations (preferably not more than a couple of hours)
elements.2211.03020_5ae42b01b361e7ddaf3958879db51: Demonstrators can be humans, other robots, or other simulated agents, and demonstrations can be collected in a variety of modes, including teleoperation, third-person video recording, and kinesthetic interactions
elements.2211.03020_d98ebd40d6786495d0e67cbd1a605: To improve the ease of filtering the data, demonstrators may automatically tag the data they are collecting as success or failure
elements.2211.03020_0776fdcccd3d43923767773c374fe: Once this data is collected, various techniques such as behavior cloning
elements.2211.03020_42a3971338b05a441fa999688f48c: are used to train a model that is then deployed as a policy by an autonomous agent.
elements.2211.03020_8050480d5748933da06f3ca5ac7de: In visual imitation learning for robotic manipulation, images (observations) and robot movements (actions) gathered from expert demonstrations are separated into observation and action pairs
elements.2211.03020_168ee1f7db8221eba032a27650ebe: The images are fed to a probabilistic transition model
elements.2211.03020_70e844d858226df9407e8c9a6efd3: that is used to compute robot actions - where
elements.2211.03020_431722c3f9996e039ec56c89c7b1c: The aim is to learn a policy
elements.2211.03020_e20b882c9bdf51c1cd04ec86804a6: Towards this end, teleoperation is an effective mode of data collection because (1) egocentric cameras on the robot can see the task (in contrast to direct human demonstration, where the demonstrator might physically obstruct the robot's view), and (2) the data is directly representative of the robot's action space and does not need to address the correspondence problem (the correspondence problem is the difficulty in matching different training data representations to the robot's possible action space)
elements.2211.03020_b8789af266d551a5ed04314872f16: However, in some cases, the teleoperation approach is not ideal because the human demonstrator may have an advantageous viewpoint compared to the viewpoint of the robot's cameras
elements.2211.03020_4f4ae485270e428ae3bf41b4152fd: When the human is able to see more than the robot can, the collected data may be of poor quality because the human leverages visual feedback information that is not captured in the egocentric robot images that are fed to the model
elements.2211.03020_79d554c67fa29bd5ab9e50d0a2632: There may also be a kinematic and force feedback mismatch between the human and the teleoperated robot because the robot's sensors may record contact forces that are not felt by the teleoperator
elements.2211.03020_e3e8390ccdf841f61ea08fa2975af: These mismatching visual and force feedback channels between the human and the robot may be mitigated by giving the human demonstrator more real-time feedback about the robot's overall state, thus altering the demonstrator's behavior
elements.2211.03020_f75bbe07b883af81c43f4ce23c22a: Haptic feedback is a promising alternative feedback channel for teleoperating physical manipulation tasks and may alter demonstrator behavior, such as the time needed to collect useful data and the quality or consistency of the data
elements.2211.03020_16f14cfc3915b6f2ae5dbde9ce265: This alteration in demonstrator behavior can impact the learned policy
elements.2211.03020_a9f773572b28200077b795424490f: The quality of the collected data plays an important role in generating autonomous actions via behavior cloning techniques
elements.2211.03020_13f8f7d6e4c549a16221c4122b657: Imagine two scenarios: Scenario A: X hours of high-quality data is collected (in this case, data collected with haptics)
elements.2211.03020_0b5bd83cd402af3062c72c7c75109: Scenario B: 2X of confusing, messy data is collected
elements.2211.03020_44bb85152d9af945fe9d5ea76e9bc: Despite Scenario B having more data, it yields to poorer performance because the imprecise data reduces training clarity
elements.2211.03020_26f840d45d78ab5eae594c33e994d: Thus, to improve the LfD process and understand the role of added haptic feedback, we address two primary research questions:
elements.2211.03020_8fd8676186c69b5c8b1695683d49e: Does haptic feedback improve demonstrator performance during example collection?
elements.2211.03020_0864c9a30bd7a798f5bc7a5557cad: Do models trained with data collected with haptic feedback lead to improved autonomous robot task performance (i.e. resultant policies)?
elements.2211.03020_e3a21f9d0295fca6d1613cbd41cac: To address these research questions, we performed a study to learn a latch door opening physical interaction task (Figure
elements.2211.03020_2c84b905d053ec782f40af90f093d: ), through human demonstration via teleoperation with and without haptic feedback
elements.2211.03020_a18469e9a3c797de257131e14a565: The results indicate that the use of haptic feedback helps with both the data quality and quantity
elements.2211.03020_c7e79fdf03cc076aea0d2f0c4837a: It is widely accepted in imitation learning that one can improve robot performance through either better model architecture or better data
elements.2211.03020_3dc2844f323e0a2690832fbb24b91: In our work, we study the latter and evaluate it at two levels: (1) Data collection and (2) Learned policy performance
elements.2211.03020_33a38c60b938e4193edd8aa8caecf: Our contribution comes from not only making the data collection faster/higher yield but also demonstrating that this change in demonstrator behavior manifests in a change in learned policy performance
elements.2211.03020_9f8d39170ece1cf350ae451fd4f07: Our results show that haptic feedback is useful for robot learning not necessarily because the task requires it; but because the quality of the collected data is higher.
elements.2211.03020_3877e40fffa53fad33fcd1a2a0a35: We consider tasks that require physical interaction between the robot end-effector and its environment
elements.2211.03020_c72ad287c75e9aa09d69673e3254a: This interaction constrains the movement of the robot and results in forces that can be used to generate haptic feedback

elements.2211.03020_1d653b15fa9c29bc5ef082ccd2325: Related work shows that it is possible to train complex manipulation behaviors from images alone

elements.2211.03020_c6bf9e21e0fc757d8cbf45b82e070: Given a collected dataset, a secondary, yet critical, challenge is how to remove low-quality data or mislabeled data from the dataset

elements.2211.03020_7b41e844eaa4abcc60f6788e14211: Other researchers equipped a robot with a pressure cuff so human demonstrators could encode stiffness profiles during example collection; they concluded that adding the stiffness profile to the control scheme increased the robot's success rate at lighting a match

elements.2211.03020_4ab475426db097460d57b244a7727: In this research work we leverage haptic feedback during the data collection phase to improve the demonstration data throughput and its quality for the purpose of training a deep visual imitation learning model.
